Introduction

Do higher film budgets lead to more box office revenue? Let's find out if there's a relationship using the movie budgets and financial performance data that I've scraped from the-numbers.com on May 1st, 2018.

Data Type Conversions

Challenge: Convert the USD_Production_Budget, USD_Worldwide_Gross, and USD_Domestic_Gross columns to a numeric format by removing $ signs and ,.

Note that domestic in this context refers to the United States.

In[8]:
data['USD_Production_Budget'] = data['USD_Production_Budget'].str.replace(r"[$,]", "", regex=True).astype(float)
data['USD_Worldwide_Gross'] = data['USD_Worldwide_Gross'].str.replace(r"[$,]", "", regex=True).astype(float)
data['USD_Domestic_Gross'] = data['USD_Domestic_Gross'].str.replace(r"[$,]", "", regex=True).astype(float)

Converting Years to Decades Trick

Challenge: Create a column in data_clean that has the decade of the release.

Here's how:

  1. Create a DatetimeIndex object from the Release_Date column.
  2. Grab all the years from the DatetimeIndex object using the .year property.
  3. Use floor division // to convert the year data to the decades of the films.
  4. Add the decades as a Decade column to the data_clean DataFrame.
In[24]:
years = pd.DatetimeIndex(data_clean['Release_Date']).year # type: ignore
decades = (years//10)*10
data_clean = data_clean.copy()
data_clean['Decades'] = decades
data_clean.head()

Separate the "old" (before 1969) and "New" (1970s onwards) Films

Challenge: Create two new DataFrames: old_films and new_films

  • old_films should include all the films before 1969 (up to and including 1969)
  • new_films should include all the films from 1970 onwards
  • How many films were released prior to 1970?
  • What was the most expensive film made prior to 1970?

old_films = data_clean[data_clean['Decades'] < 1970]
new_films = data_clean[data_clean['Decades'] >= 1970]
highest_budget = old_films.nlargest(1, 'USD_Production_Budget')

Run Your Own Regression with scikit-learn

$$ REV \hat ENUE = \theta _0 + \theta _1 BUDGET$$

In[28]:
new_movie = LinearRegression()
# Explanatory Variable(s) or Feature(s)
X = pd.DataFrame(new_films, columns=['USD_Production_Budget'])

# Response Variable or Target
y = pd.DataFrame(new_films, columns=['USD_Worldwide_Gross'])
new_movie.fit(X, y)
print("Intercept:", new_movie.intercept_)
print("Coefficient:", new_movie.coef_)
print("R Score:", new_movie.score(X, y))

Intercept: [-8650768.00661042]
Coefficient: [[3.12259592]]
R Score: 0.5577032617720403

regression = LinearRegression()
# Explanatory Variable(s) or Feature(s)
X = pd.DataFrame(old_films, columns=['USD_Production_Budget'])

# Response Variable or Target

Intercept: 22821538.635080386
Coefficient: 1.6477131440107315
R Score: 0.02937258620576877

Use Your Model to Make a Prediction

We just estimated the slope and intercept! Remember that our Linear Model has the following form:

$$ REV \hat ENUE = \theta _0 + \theta _1 BUDGET$$
